WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:05.000
What are the elements of your strategy?

00:05.000 --> 00:11.000
Global marketing strategy in the 21st century.

00:11.000 --> 00:17.000
What elements should your strategy contain?

00:17.000 --> 00:25.000
Or what aspects should you think about to make your company successful?

00:26.000 --> 00:34.000
The first element is a clear shift.

00:34.000 --> 00:49.000
The shift is that the units of strategic planning are more and more often represented by regional or global markets.

00:49.000 --> 00:52.000
What examples can we see?

00:52.000 --> 01:01.000
First, we can see that there are industries whose markets are global in nature.

01:01.000 --> 01:16.000
For example, the aircraft industry market, where there are a limited number of customers who have more or less similar requirements.

01:16.000 --> 01:27.000
Thus, the supplier can consider this market as global and no longer divide the countries.

01:27.000 --> 01:36.000
The second situation is that companies are gradually starting to focus on the global market.

01:36.000 --> 01:42.000
These are some specific segments.

01:42.000 --> 01:46.000
For example, global teenagers.

01:46.000 --> 01:51.000
This segment is considered one of the most attractive.

01:51.000 --> 02:00.000
Why? Because it has a number of people comparable to China's population.

02:00.000 --> 02:04.000
There are about 1.3 billion teenagers.

02:04.000 --> 02:20.000
This group has good financial capabilities due to the fact that their parents provide them with pocket money.

02:20.000 --> 02:31.000
We see that companies like Coca-Cola, MTV, and Svoch are actively using the services of this segment.

02:31.000 --> 02:44.000
Another example is the emergence of national marketing, in particular, the emergence of Muslim marketing.

02:44.000 --> 02:48.000
Here we see how LG used this opportunity.

02:48.000 --> 02:54.000
They invented the first so-called Muslim mobile phone.

02:54.000 --> 02:58.000
It is different from the usual one because it has a built-in compass.

02:58.000 --> 03:05.000
Therefore, a person can turn to the East during prayer.

03:05.000 --> 03:18.000
The second aspect that you should pay attention to today, while developing your strategy, is the coordination of the marketing strategy with production and logistics distribution.

03:18.000 --> 03:27.000
It is worth paying attention to Inditex and one of its most famous brands, the Zara retail chain.

03:27.000 --> 03:33.000
Zara successfully coordinates all three elements.

03:33.000 --> 03:38.000
Let's start with the fact that Zara listens to the market very carefully.

03:38.000 --> 03:40.000
How does it listen to the market?

03:40.000 --> 03:49.000
First of all, the company's designers are present at all fashion shows, whether in Milan, Paris, or New York.

03:49.000 --> 04:00.000
The company closely monitors various publications in the fashion press, TV stories.

04:00.000 --> 04:07.000
It sends its experts to the places of the fashion youth.

04:07.000 --> 04:16.000
A very important element of the company's ear is the Zara retail chain.

04:16.000 --> 04:22.000
This allows the company to really understand consumers.

04:22.000 --> 04:29.000
Moreover, Zara has a much smaller percentage of unsuccessful products than the average industry.

04:29.000 --> 04:32.000
1% versus 10%.

04:32.000 --> 04:42.000
Despite the fact that the company offers about 11,000 names to the market annually versus 2-3 in the industry.

04:42.000 --> 04:47.000
In addition, the company does it much faster than its competitors.

04:47.000 --> 04:54.000
Zara is able to deliver its collection to its stores twice a week.

04:54.000 --> 05:09.000
The full development of the design and production takes 4-5 months versus 6 months for the development of the design and 3 months for production.

05:09.000 --> 05:15.000
We see that the company is already winning over its competitors.

05:15.000 --> 05:32.000
In addition, the processes of delivery of finished products from the distribution center, which is located in Spain, are very well laid out.

05:32.000 --> 05:47.000
Logistics inside Europe takes a maximum of 24 hours, outside Europe 36 hours.

05:47.000 --> 06:01.000
Everything is built on the fact that the company has the opportunity to present its consumer with a modern design much faster than its competitors.

06:01.000 --> 06:12.000
The third important aspect is the ability to transfer skills, knowledge, and experience across national markets.

06:13.000 --> 06:17.000
Here is a very curious example of a company like Levi Strauss.

06:17.000 --> 06:28.000
In particular, the company collects its managers from all over the world twice a year.

06:28.000 --> 06:41.000
They have the opportunity to exchange ideas, skills, and models that could have been developed for a certain national market.

06:41.000 --> 06:49.000
They have the opportunity to gradually transfer to other country markets.

06:50.000 --> 06:58.000
The next element of the global marketing strategy is the creation of a coordinated brand architecture for international markets.

06:58.000 --> 07:01.000
This is a very difficult task.

07:01.000 --> 07:07.000
We see that a company like Unilever has been going for a long time.

07:07.000 --> 07:15.000
This led to the fact that by the end of the 1990s, the portfolio of company brands had risen to 1,600.

07:15.000 --> 07:24.000
This led to significant increases in costs and an increasing difficulty in managing such a machine.

07:24.000 --> 07:45.000
What we are seeing now, or rather, this process began at the beginning of the century, is that companies that initially appeared on the market through absorption and accumulation of brands in their portfolios

07:45.000 --> 07:48.000
gradually began to get rid of brands.

07:48.000 --> 07:54.000
In particular, Unilever has already managed to reduce its portfolio by four times.

07:54.000 --> 07:56.000
And it seems that this is not the limit.

07:56.000 --> 08:08.000
This significantly facilitates management and increases the profits of this portfolio.

08:09.000 --> 08:17.000
The next important aspect of the global marketing strategy is the change in the relationship in marketing channels.

08:17.000 --> 08:21.000
We need to adapt to these changes.

08:21.000 --> 08:23.000
What changes do we see?

08:23.000 --> 08:31.000
One of the obvious changes is that the strength of retailers has increased significantly.

08:32.000 --> 08:39.000
And, oddly enough, sometimes even large manufacturers have to make concessions.

08:39.000 --> 08:50.000
In particular, it is quite curious that until 2000, such a well-known large American company as Kellogg, which produces dry breakfasts,

08:50.000 --> 09:00.000
wrote on its packaging, if it does not say Kellogg on the packaging, it means Kellogg inside.

09:00.000 --> 09:06.000
But since that moment, since 2000, this is no longer true,

09:06.000 --> 09:14.000
because the German Aldi network has put conditions on all manufacturers of branded products

09:14.000 --> 09:19.000
to supply their products to this network exclusively under the private brand of this network.

09:19.000 --> 09:21.000
That is, Aldi.

09:21.000 --> 09:31.000
And the company had to make concessions, otherwise its products would simply be washed out of the shelves.

09:31.000 --> 09:45.000
The second aspect to pay attention to is that the manufacturer has now received an additional channel of direct access to the end consumer.

09:45.000 --> 09:46.000
The Internet.

09:46.000 --> 09:53.000
And here we are smoothly moving on to the sixth point, the development of an effective Internet strategy.

09:53.000 --> 09:56.000
And here you will have to think about the following.

09:56.000 --> 10:10.000
What role will your site play in the interaction with consumers, suppliers and other interested parties?

10:10.000 --> 10:12.000
And the second aspect.

10:12.000 --> 10:15.000
Will you use the Internet as a means of production?

10:15.000 --> 10:25.000
And here we can look at the example of Levis Strauss, who created a new business for himself.

10:25.000 --> 10:29.000
This is an Internet sample of Levis Strauss.

10:29.000 --> 10:36.000
That is, you, as a consumer, can go to the Levis page, enter your parameters,

10:36.000 --> 10:40.000
and then gradually create jeans for yourself.

10:40.000 --> 10:47.000
Choosing a color, choosing a style, choosing the number of rivets or a line.

10:47.000 --> 10:50.000
Everything you like most.

10:50.000 --> 11:00.000
At the same time, the company states that only six basic classic models will be supplied to the traditional retail.

11:00.000 --> 11:02.000
Everything else is on the Internet.

11:02.000 --> 11:09.000
Developing your global marketing strategy, you will need to make a number of key decisions

11:09.000 --> 11:15.000
in order to clearly decide how you will work in the international markets.

11:15.000 --> 11:23.000
And the first thing you have to start with is to ask a general, fundamental question.

11:23.000 --> 11:27.000
Will you go to the international markets or not?

11:27.000 --> 11:31.000
Today we assume that the answer to this question is positive.

11:31.000 --> 11:38.000
And then you will need to make a number of decisions, but already in the complex.

11:38.000 --> 11:44.000
These mutually related decisions suggest answers to such questions.

11:44.000 --> 11:48.000
Which markets to enter? How to enter these markets?

11:48.000 --> 11:57.000
Here you have to decide on the model of entry, whether there will be export, licensing, joint venture, or something else.

11:57.000 --> 12:04.000
And the sequence of entry, that is, whether you will enter the international markets in a sequence,

12:04.000 --> 12:09.000
or you will dare to enter a number of markets at the same time.

12:09.000 --> 12:16.000
The next aspect to deal with is the marketing program.

12:16.000 --> 12:20.000
And here you will need to answer a number of questions.

12:20.000 --> 12:23.000
What will you offer foreign consumers?

12:23.000 --> 12:26.000
At what price? What channels of production will you use?

12:26.000 --> 12:29.000
What means of promotion will you choose?

12:29.000 --> 12:35.000
And finally, you will need to decide how to organize international marketing activities.

12:35.000 --> 12:40.000
That is, decide who will be responsible for these operations.

12:40.000 --> 12:47.000
In case you are not yet very serious about export activities,

12:47.000 --> 12:58.000
it can be one person, or it can be a complex matrix structure.

12:58.000 --> 13:03.000
But before we move on to the instrumental part,

13:03.000 --> 13:09.000
I would like to warn you about seven so-called international marketing traps.

13:09.000 --> 13:15.000
The first trap is the choice of a country or market according to the criteria of size and demand.

13:15.000 --> 13:25.000
It should be said that many companies choose such markets as the Indian market or the Chinese market.

13:25.000 --> 13:32.000
Assuming that the population is large, the demand for their products will be high.

13:32.000 --> 13:35.000
But you need to be very careful with this,

13:35.000 --> 13:44.000
because a large number of people does not mean that this population, for example, will accept your product.

13:44.000 --> 13:47.000
Or that it will be able to pay for your product.

13:47.000 --> 13:50.000
Therefore, you need to be careful here.

13:50.000 --> 13:54.000
The next trap is underestimating existing competitors.

13:54.000 --> 14:01.000
Again, many companies, in particular American and European companies that enter the Chinese market,

14:01.000 --> 14:08.000
somehow did not fully recognize the strength of potential competitors.

14:08.000 --> 14:14.000
In particular, even in such specific markets as the turbine market,

14:14.000 --> 14:23.000
companies found that after some time, in addition to their high-quality products,

14:23.000 --> 14:28.000
a similar Chinese product appeared at a much more attractive price,

14:28.000 --> 14:32.000
and consumers began to switch to this product.

14:32.000 --> 14:35.000
Therefore, be careful with your competitors.

14:35.000 --> 14:42.000
Third, it is the expectation that motivation and benefits for consumers will be similar around the world.

14:42.000 --> 14:48.000
Here is a curious example of Unilever, which introduced its Knorr soups to the Indian market.

14:48.000 --> 14:56.000
It seems that when the product itself was tested, consumers said that the product was good.

14:56.000 --> 15:04.000
But nevertheless, the sales were ridiculous, the company did not achieve the desired results.

15:04.000 --> 15:11.000
Moreover, attempts to understand why this is happening did not immediately bear fruit.

15:11.000 --> 15:18.000
It turned out that Indian women consider this product as a surrogate.

15:18.000 --> 15:26.000
And their conscience simply does not allow them to feed their beloved family with what they consider to be a fake product,

15:26.000 --> 15:33.000
because they do not need time to cook it, and their soul does not invest in it.

15:33.000 --> 15:37.000
The next trap is the entry into the market at an unfair price.

15:37.000 --> 15:41.000
There are two extremes here.

15:41.000 --> 15:44.000
On the one hand, you can enter the market at a too low price,

15:44.000 --> 15:48.000
and on the other hand, you can enter the market at a too high price.

15:48.000 --> 15:50.000
What is the first two options dangerous for?

15:50.000 --> 15:52.000
The price is too low.

15:52.000 --> 15:57.000
A price too low can lead to the fact that your company will be accused of dumping.

15:57.000 --> 16:03.000
This means anti-dumping proceedings, this means very serious fines.

16:03.000 --> 16:05.000
The second aspect.

16:05.000 --> 16:14.000
Here you can ask yourself a question, in fact, in different cases, whether it is important or not.

16:14.000 --> 16:18.000
But nevertheless, if we go to the new market,

16:18.000 --> 16:21.000
it is clear that the consumer does not yet know our product,

16:21.000 --> 16:28.000
and we need to inform him somehow about our product, to convince him to buy our product.

16:28.000 --> 16:36.000
If your price is too low, what will you use to advertise, promote your product?

16:36.000 --> 16:39.000
Now let's look at the too high price.

16:40.000 --> 16:48.000
In this situation, it may happen that you will definitely be present in the market,

16:48.000 --> 16:52.000
but this presence will be only conditional,

16:52.000 --> 16:59.000
because the consumer may not want to pay or will not be able to pay for your product.

16:59.000 --> 17:04.000
In particular, Jaguar faced this problem on the Japanese market.

17:04.000 --> 17:09.000
Although it would seem that the Japanese market, there is even such a stereotype,

17:09.000 --> 17:16.000
that there the consumer is exclusively sensitive to quality and pays less attention to prices.

17:16.000 --> 17:20.000
And yet, even there, Jaguar, having set too high a price,

17:20.000 --> 17:26.000
was in a losing situation, a very low degree of penetration into the market.

17:26.000 --> 17:33.000
The next problem or trap is entering the market without planning the expansion process.

17:33.000 --> 17:40.000
You must immediately, today, when you are thinking about the possibility of expansion,

17:40.000 --> 17:44.000
clearly plan and answer a number of very important questions.

17:44.000 --> 17:50.000
The next trap is working with bad distributors.

17:50.000 --> 17:56.000
Indeed, very often your success in the foreign market will depend on this,

17:56.000 --> 17:59.000
or very much on this.

17:59.000 --> 18:03.000
Will you have a good partner, your distributor,

18:03.000 --> 18:09.000
who will be able to tell you where to go around some underwater stones

18:09.000 --> 18:14.000
and how to better present your product to the end consumer.

18:14.000 --> 18:18.000
Here, the next trap is quite close,

18:18.000 --> 18:21.000
it is the loss of the brand's exclusivity.

18:21.000 --> 18:28.000
In the case of a company that has a very serious brand,

18:28.000 --> 18:32.000
which has an exclusive image,

18:32.000 --> 18:39.000
for such companies it can be destructive to work with bad partners or distributors.

18:39.000 --> 18:45.000
In particular, the example of the company Lacoste,

18:45.000 --> 18:49.000
which was released on the American market, became a classic, one might say.

18:49.000 --> 18:55.000
And they decided to use licensing as a model of entering the market.

18:55.000 --> 19:01.000
They found a local company that bought the right to use their Lacoste brand.

19:01.000 --> 19:04.000
But what did this licensee do?

19:04.000 --> 19:11.000
He saw that the demand for Lacoste products was very high,

19:11.000 --> 19:16.000
and in fact, he flooded the market with Lacoste shirts.

19:16.000 --> 19:20.000
Moreover, he simply reduced the prices.

19:20.000 --> 19:27.000
The company observed for several years that the exclusivity of its brand went down,

19:27.000 --> 19:29.000
it became available.

19:29.000 --> 19:36.000
Therefore, after a while, a decision was made to leave the American market.

19:36.000 --> 19:40.000
And the company only returned to this market after a while.

19:40.000 --> 19:42.000
And now it was only export.

19:42.000 --> 19:45.000
It was a truly exclusive brand,

19:45.000 --> 19:50.000
supported by the fact that it was sold in a limited number of boutiques.

19:50.000 --> 19:52.000
It was a fairly high price,

19:52.000 --> 19:57.000
confirming the prestige, exclusivity and quality of this brand.

19:57.000 --> 20:05.000
Now let's finally figure out how to make these decisions.

20:05.000 --> 20:08.000
What tools can help us here?

20:08.000 --> 20:15.000
The first thing we should think about is the decision to leave the international market.

20:15.000 --> 20:18.000
What alternatives do we have here?

20:18.000 --> 20:25.000
It is clear that on the one hand, we can make a decision to enter the international market immediately.

20:25.000 --> 20:29.000
On the other hand, this decision can be postponed,

20:29.000 --> 20:36.000
or there may be a situation when you do not consider entering the international market.

20:36.000 --> 20:40.000
This is not an option for you, for one reason or another.

20:40.000 --> 20:45.000
What reasons will you choose from these alternatives?

20:45.000 --> 20:48.000
What will affect your decision?

20:48.000 --> 20:56.000
Your decision will be influenced by the goals, resources of your company,

20:56.000 --> 20:59.000
motivation of your top managers.

20:59.000 --> 21:07.000
By the way, it will largely depend on the experience of international activities,

21:07.000 --> 21:14.000
top managers, owners, or leading employees of the company.

21:14.000 --> 21:22.000
You will also pay attention to the competitiveness of your product.

21:22.000 --> 21:28.000
Do you have a product or service that can be in demand in foreign markets?

21:28.000 --> 21:35.000
The opportunities of international markets will be a noticeable factor of influence for you.

21:35.000 --> 21:39.000
What else should we pay attention to?

21:39.000 --> 21:48.000
You should decide whether you have enough resources to enter the foreign market,

21:48.000 --> 21:53.000
or you need to find help and support.

21:53.000 --> 21:55.000
In what aspects?

21:55.000 --> 21:58.000
It can be providing information.

21:58.000 --> 22:04.000
Then you will look for information about professional associations,

22:04.000 --> 22:09.000
whether commercial or non-commercial,

22:09.000 --> 22:17.000
that can help you in your export operations or enter the international market.

22:18.000 --> 22:24.000
It can be a situation when you need help from a resource group.

22:24.000 --> 22:30.000
Then you can try to join some companies,

22:30.000 --> 22:35.000
to create a network to enter the foreign market.

22:35.000 --> 22:42.000
You should decide what you do and what you can outsource.

22:43.000 --> 22:51.000
It is quite often observed that companies outsourcing to some external companies

22:51.000 --> 22:55.000
or organizations, ask questions like

22:55.000 --> 22:58.000
conducting marketing research in foreign markets.

22:58.000 --> 23:01.000
Of course, a specific qualification is needed for this.

23:01.000 --> 23:09.000
But sometimes companies that are just starting to master the international market,

23:09.000 --> 23:14.000
they outsource almost all of their export operations.

23:14.000 --> 23:16.000
It is also possible.

23:16.000 --> 23:23.000
Now, if we have made this decision,

23:23.000 --> 23:30.000
we need to go through some important element,

23:30.000 --> 23:33.000
that is, to conduct a strategic analysis,

23:33.000 --> 23:38.000
to try to plan our activities,

23:38.000 --> 23:42.000
what elements will be very important here,

23:42.000 --> 23:44.000
what should you decide on.

23:44.000 --> 23:47.000
The first thing you need to decide on is the competition level.

23:47.000 --> 23:54.000
That is, what products of the market and in which country you need to be present.

23:54.000 --> 23:59.000
There can be different possibilities.

23:59.000 --> 24:03.000
I will give you an example of Heineken company,

24:03.000 --> 24:12.000
which for some time was thinking about how to understand the market in foreign markets,

24:12.000 --> 24:17.000
which it was going to introduce non-alcoholic beer Buckler.

24:17.000 --> 24:19.000
It would seem that everything is clear.

24:19.000 --> 24:28.000
You can choose exclusively the non-alcoholic beer market as a market and a competition level.

24:28.000 --> 24:32.000
And then you will compete with non-alcoholic beer manufacturers.

24:32.000 --> 24:36.000
But there is another situation, when you can look at this market more broadly.

24:36.000 --> 24:44.000
And you can say that you are competing in the market of non-alcoholic beverages.

24:44.000 --> 24:46.000
And then what?

24:46.000 --> 24:54.000
It's just water, it's some cola, and so on.

24:54.000 --> 24:56.000
That is, much more broadly.

24:56.000 --> 24:58.000
How to understand what is more profitable for you?

24:58.000 --> 25:02.000
This is your goal, and these are your resources.

25:04.000 --> 25:13.000
Speaking of competition, you also need to understand what is more important for you.

25:13.000 --> 25:18.000
You can create new products for existing customers.

25:18.000 --> 25:29.000
If, of course, it was about the fact that in one way or another, you already have some customers in these foreign markets.

25:29.000 --> 25:37.000
Or you start looking for new consumers for existing products.

25:37.000 --> 25:41.000
The next block is goals and strategy tasks.

25:42.000 --> 25:51.000
Here you need to decide on the volume, growth of sales, profitability of sales.

25:51.000 --> 25:59.000
You need to decide what level of capital profitability or investment you want to get.

25:59.000 --> 26:06.000
You need to decide on the intensity and sources of money flows.

26:06.000 --> 26:16.000
That is, all the goals that can be transformed into the final financial result.

26:16.000 --> 26:18.000
You need to understand all this.

26:18.000 --> 26:24.000
And always, if it is immeasurable, how to manage it?

26:24.000 --> 26:29.000
Accordingly, you must give a numerical answer to each question.

26:29.000 --> 26:34.000
What is the level of profitability? What is the level of profitability?

26:35.000 --> 26:38.000
You need to give a qualitative answer, not quantitative.

26:38.000 --> 26:45.000
You need to answer the question, what needs to be done to strengthen competitive advantages?

26:45.000 --> 26:48.000
And in fact, it can be even more important.

26:48.000 --> 26:54.000
You need to understand the competitive advantages that you have.

26:54.000 --> 26:57.000
Will they work in international markets?

26:57.000 --> 27:00.000
Or do you need to look for something else?

27:01.000 --> 27:05.000
The next block is related to the distribution of resources.

27:05.000 --> 27:12.000
We say that all companies have limited resources.

27:12.000 --> 27:20.000
And your decision is how to distribute them between countries or product markets.

27:20.000 --> 27:29.000
Very often, at the first stages, we see that a lion's share of resources is still allocated to the domestic market.

27:29.000 --> 27:37.000
And only the minimum resources are allocated to conquer international markets.

27:37.000 --> 27:40.000
The goal of your strategy.

27:40.000 --> 27:43.000
Here you return to this question.

27:43.000 --> 27:47.000
Maybe at the first stages it will be the right decision for you.

27:47.000 --> 27:53.000
And the second question is how best to divide the available resources between functional units.

27:53.000 --> 27:57.000
To more successfully implement the strategy.

27:57.000 --> 28:03.000
Companies usually add international units to their functional structure.

28:03.000 --> 28:08.000
And then there are problems inside the company.

28:08.000 --> 28:15.000
How to distribute resources between functional units that are oriented to the domestic market.

28:15.000 --> 28:20.000
And those units that are oriented to the external market.

28:20.000 --> 28:25.000
The next block of questions is related to the sources of competitive advantage.

28:25.000 --> 28:31.000
And here you need to understand what are the sources for your company.

28:31.000 --> 28:33.000
What do you have?

28:33.000 --> 28:37.000
Maybe it's access to cheaper resources.

28:37.000 --> 28:39.000
Or vice versa.

28:39.000 --> 28:48.000
You have a highly qualified workforce.

28:48.000 --> 28:52.000
And this is closely related to the next question.

28:52.000 --> 28:56.000
How long will you be able to maintain this advantage?

28:56.000 --> 29:08.000
If you have access to something cheap, you will not be able to maintain this advantage for long.

29:08.000 --> 29:16.000
And if you have access to something cheap, you will not be able to maintain this advantage for long.

29:16.000 --> 29:24.000
And as we said, you need to understand what you need to do to strengthen these competitive advantages.

29:24.000 --> 29:28.000
Or maybe it's really about buying something new.

29:28.000 --> 29:31.000
And finally, the sources of the synergetic effect.

